      "ans": "B",
      "exp": "重點：Wilms tumor 佔 childhood cancers 約 6%，美國每年約 500 cases，是 children 最常見 abdominal tumor。Median age 3-4 years，75% 在 age 5 前診斷；4-8% 是 bilateral tumors，bilateral cases median age 更低，約 2-3 years。",
      "exp_en": "Key point: Wilms tumor accounts for about 6% of childhood cancers, with about 500 cases per year in the United States, and is the most common abdominal tumor in children. Median age is 3-4 years; 75% are diagnosed before age 5. About 4-8% are bilateral, and bilateral cases present earlier, around age 2-3 years.",
      "A": "GI/pelvic bleeding: Stabilize、transfusion/IR/endoscopy if needed; RT 對 bleeding control 很有效; 8 Gy ×1、14.8 Gy/4 QUADSHOT、20 Gy/5、30 Gy/10",
      "A_en": "GI / pelvic bleeding: Stabilize, transfuse, and use IR or endoscopy when needed.; Radiotherapy is highly effective for bleeding control.; 8 Gy ×1, 14.8 Gy in 4 fractions QUADSHOT, 20 Gy in 5 fractions, 30 Gy in 10 fractions.",
      "B": "Wilms tumor 佔 childhood cancers 約 6%，美國每年約 500 cases，是 children 最常見 abdominal tumor。Median age 3-4 years，75% 在 age 5 前診斷；4-8% 是 bilateral tumors，bilateral cases median age 更低，約 2-3 years。",
      "B_en": "Wilms tumor accounts for about 6% of childhood cancers, with about 500 cases per year in the United States, and is the most common abdominal tumor in children. Median age is 3-4 years; 75% are diagnosed before age 5. About 4-8% are bilateral, and bilateral cases present earlier, around age 2-3 years.",
      "C": "H&N bleeding: 先確保 airway 與 hemodynamics; QUADSHOT 適合 frail / palliative H&N; 14 Gy/4 Fx BID ×2 days，可 q4wk 重複",
      "C_en": "Head and neck bleeding: Secure airway and hemodynamics first.; QUADSHOT is useful for frail or palliative head and neck patients.; 14 Gy in 4 fractions BID over 2 days, repeat every 4 weeks if appropriate.",
      "D": "8 Gy/1 Fx: Poor PS、very limited prognosis；SCORAD 未達 non-inferiority，但 poor PS 可考慮",
      "D_en": "8 Gy in 1 fraction: Poor performance status and very limited prognosis; SCORAD did not meet formal non-inferiority, but this remains reasonable for poor-performance patients."
